Question: The sodium salt of sulfonamide in aqueous solutions are:
CorrectExplanation:
• Conjugate base of a weak acid is a strong base
  • Conjugate base of a strong acid is a weak base
  • Conjugate acid of a weak base is a strong base
  • Conjugate acid of strong base is a weak base


Sulfonamide is a weak acid. Hence, its sodium salt, which is its conjugate base, is strongly basic.


Additional Information:

This question was repeated twice last November 2022 PhLE in Module 1. Make sure to familiarize yourself with the given question and take time to rationalize further if you have the time to do so.
IncorrectExplanation:
• Conjugate base of a weak acid is a strong base
  • Conjugate base of a strong acid is a weak base
  • Conjugate acid of a weak base is a strong base
  • Conjugate acid of strong base is a weak base

Sulfonamide is a weak acid. Hence, its sodium salt, which is its conjugate base, is strongly basic.

B 🡪 Also known as carbolic acid; for the assay and estimation of phenols & related compounds, bromine 10th solution (koppeschaar’s solution) is commonly used.

Question: A principle which states that in the ground state of an atom, electrons fill orbitals of the lowest available energy levels before occupying higher level.
CorrectExplanation:
BEQ!


Rule of Maximum Multiplicity

  • More commonly known as Hund’s rule
  • Orbitals are filled up singly before pairing up.
  • Most stable arrangement of electron in subshells is the one with greatest number of parallel spins.

Indeterminacy Principle

  • More commonly known as Heisenberg’s Uncertainty Principle
  • Impossible to predict/accurately determine the particle’s velocity (position & momentum)

Pauli’s Exclusion Principle (BEQ!)

  • An atom cannot have 2 electrons in the same energy level or orbital that have the same set of quantum numbers.
IncorrectExplanation:
BEQ!


Rule of Maximum Multiplicity

  • More commonly known as Hund’s rule
  • Orbitals are filled up singly before pairing up.
  • Most stable arrangement of electron in subshells is the one with greatest number of parallel spins.

Indeterminacy Principle

  • More commonly known as Heisenberg’s Uncertainty Principle
  • Impossible to predict/accurately determine the particle’s velocity (position & momentum)

Pauli’s Exclusion Principle (BEQ!)

  • An atom cannot have 2 electrons in the same energy level or orbital that have the same set of quantum numbers.

Question: A drug that forms stable complexes with copper (II) ions. Such a complex was used as an antibiotic for treating diarrhea and skin infections.
CorrectExplanation:
BEQ!

Piperazine

  • MOA: Acts as a γ-aminobutyric acid (GABA) agonist, causing chloride channel opening, neural hyperpolarization and flaccid paralysis of susceptible parasites.

Mefloquine

  • MOA: Specifically targets the 80S ribosome of the Plasmodium falciparum, inhibiting protein synthesis and causing subsequent schizonticidal effects.

Diiodohydroxyquinoline

  • Popularly known as Iodoquinol

  • MOA: the exact mechanism of action of iodoquinol is unknown. Iodoquinol acts against the trophozoites of Entamoeba histolytica. Iodoquinol produces its amoebicidal effect at the site of infection, since it is poorly absorbed from the gastrointestinal tract and can reach high concentrations in the intestinal lumen.

Question: How many pi electrons are present in carbon dioxide?
CorrectExplanation:
BEC!

Carbon dioxide contains two pi bonds. Each pi bond contains two electrons. In totality, since CO2 contains two pi bonds, it can be inferred that there are four pi electrons present in the compound.
IncorrectExplanation:
BEC!

Carbon dioxide contains two pi bonds. Each pi bond contains two electrons. In totality, since CO2 contains two pi bonds, it can be inferred that there are four pi electrons present in the compound.

Question: What is the IUPAC name of this compound?
CorrectExplanation:
IUPAC Rules for Alkene and Cycloalkene Nomenclature

  1. The ene suffix (ending) indicates an alkene or cycloalkene.
  2. The longest chain chosen for the root name must include both carbon atoms of the double bond.
  3. The root chain is numbered from the end nearest a double bond carbon atom. If the double bond is in the center of the chain, the nearest substituent rule is used to determine the end where numbering starts.
  4. The smaller of the two numbers designating the carbon atoms of the double bond is used as the double bond locator. If more than one double bond is present the compound is named as a diene, triene or equivalent prefix indicating the number of double bonds, and each double bond is assigned a locator number.
  5. In cycloalkenes the double bond carbons are assigned ring locations #1 and #2. Which of the two is #1 may be determined by the nearest substituent rule.
  6. Substituent groups containing double bonds are:
H2C=CH- Vinyl group
H2C=CH-CH2- Allyl group

Question: Example of isosteric pairs: I.  -OH and -SH II.  COO- and SO2NR- III. -H and -F IV. C=O and O=S=O V.  -OH and -NH2
CorrectExplanation:
Bioisosterism

  • Substitute or groups with similar physical or chemical properties that impart similar biological properties to a chemical compound.

Purpose:

  • Enhance the desired biological or physical properties of a compound without making significant changes in chemical

  • Increase potency

  • Decrease side effects

  • Increase duration of action by altering metabolism

  • Isosteric analogs may act antagonistically with the parent molecule.

Example of bioisosteric replacements:

  • Fluorine vs. Hydrogen
  • Hydroxyl vs. Amino acids
  • Hydroxyl vs. Thiol groups
  • Methyl, Methoxyl, Hydroxyl, Amino groups vs. Hydrogen
  • Fluoro, Chloro, and Bromo, Thiol vs. Methyl and other small alkyl groups

Question: Consider three 1-L flasks at STP. Flask A contains NO2 gas, flask B contains N2 gas, and flask C contains N2 gas. Which contains the largest number of molecules?
CorrectExplanation: Avogadro's hypothesis states that equal volumes of all gases at the same temperature and pressure contain equal numbers of particles. Since the total volume that a gas occupies is made up primarily of the empty space between the particles, the actual size of the particles themselves is nearly negligible.
IncorrectExplanation: Avogadro's hypothesis states that equal volumes of all gases at the same temperature and pressure contain equal numbers of particles. Since the total volume that a gas occupies is made up primarily of the empty space between the particles, the actual size of the particles themselves is nearly negligible.

Question: Which of the following facts illustrates the effect of nature of reactants on reaction rates?
Answer1: In 0.1 M HCl solution, powdered CaCO3 dissolves faster than a chunk of CaCO3.
Answer2: Magnesium dissolves faster in 1M HCl than in 6M HCl solution
Answer3: In 3 M HCl solution, Mg ribbon reacts faster than iron filling
Answer4: Formation of cloudy mixture from decomposition of sodium thiosulfate in water takes shorter time at 50 degrees Celsius than at 25 degrees Celsius.
CorrectExplanation:
BEC!

Factors Affecting Chemical Kinetics

1) Nature of Reactants

  • Physical state affects reactivity, i.e., gas is more reactive.

2) Temperature

  • The higher the temperature, the higher the kinetic energy, the higher the mobility of molecules, the higher the frequency of collisions, the faster the rate of reaction.

3) Concentration of Reactants

  • The higher the concentration, the faster the rate of reaction. EXCEPT for zero order chemical reaction.

4) Catalyst is a substance which speeds up the rate of chemical reaction:

  • Lowering the activation energy.
  • Makes the reaction proceed in a multi-step process of which each step has a lower activation energy compared to the uncatalyzed reaction.

5) Surface Area

  • The higher the surface area, the smaller the particle size, the faster the rate of reaction.


A 🡪 Since a “chunk” of CaCO3 has a smaller particle size than a “powdered” CaCO3, it can be inferred that the former has a higher surface area; hence, the faster the rate of reaction.

B 🡪 Magnesium should dissolve faster in 6M HCl solution than in 1M HCl solution owing to the former’s higher concentration. It is said that as the concentration of reactant decreased in the reaction, then the rate of reaction also decreases. On one hand, the higher the concentration of a reactant, the more efficient the reaction can take place.

C 🡪 Since Mg is more reactive than Fe as elucidated in the reactivity series of metals, it can be concluded that the former has a higher potential of proceeding in a reaction than the latter, making Mg achieved a faster rate of reaction than Fe.

D 🡪 It should take a longer time for the higher temperature to form a cloudy mixture as it has higher kinetic energy, higher molecule mobility, higher frequency of collisions, which inevitably results to a faster rate of reaction. A clear and transparent mixture is much more a desired outcome of the higher temperature than a cloudy one on the basis of its attributes & characteristics.

Question: Characteristics of Arrhenius Theory of Electrolyte Dissociation include the following:I.   Dissociation is the process of separation of charged particlesthat already exist in a compound.II.  Dissociation is possible only when there are ionic bonds in acompound.III.  Dissociation will either produced charged particles orelectrically neutral particles.IV.  Dissociation is reversible.
CorrectExplanation:
The Arrhenius Theory of Electrolyte Dissociation was based on the observation that the ionization potential of water was greater than that of sodium chloride and KCl. This was the reason that, when two solutions of NaCl and KCl were mixed, ions of Cl-, and OH- ions were generated. In other words, it was observed that the Cl- ion concentration of solution decreased as NaCl and KCl were mixed. This is called the Arrhenius dissociation theory.


Characteristics of Electrolytic Dissociation

  1. Dissociation is the process of separation of charged particles that already exist in a compound.
  2. Dissociation involves ionic compounds.
  3. Dissociation will either produce charged particles or electrically neutral particles.
  4. Dissociation is reversible.
  5. Dissociation is possible only when there are ionic bonds in a compound.
IncorrectExplanation:
The Arrhenius Theory of Electrolyte Dissociation was based on the observation that the ionization potential of water was greater than that of sodium chloride and KCl. This was the reason that, when two solutions of NaCl and KCl were mixed, ions of Cl-, and OH- ions were generated. In other words, it was observed that the Cl- ion concentration of solution decreased as NaCl and KCl were mixed. This is called the Arrhenius dissociation theory.


Characteristics of Electrolytic Dissociation

  1. Dissociation is the process of separation of charged particles that already exist in a compound.
  2. Dissociation involves ionic compounds.
  3. Dissociation will either produce charged particles or electrically neutral particles.
  4. Dissociation is reversible.
  5. Dissociation is possible only when there are ionic bonds in a compound.

Question: Which of the following elements are amphoteric? I.  Beryllium II.  Zinc III. Aluminum IV. Calcium
CorrectExplanation:
Amphoteric species are molecules or ions that can react as an acid as well as a base. The word has Greek origins, amphoteroi meaning “both”. Many metals such as copper, zinc, tin, lead, aluminum, and beryllium form amphoteric oxides or hydroxides. Amphoterism depends on the oxidation state of the oxide.


For example, zinc oxide (ZnO) reacts with both acids and with bases: 

  • In ACID: ZnO + 2H+ -> Zn2+ + H2O

  • In BASE: ZnO + 2OH- + H2O -> [Zn(OH)4]2-

This reactivity can be used to separate different cations, such as zinc (II), which dissolves in base, from manganese (II), which does not dissolve in base.
IncorrectExplanation:
Amphoteric species are molecules or ions that can react as an acid as well as a base. The word has Greek origins, amphoteroi meaning “both”. Many metals such as copper, zinc, tin, lead, aluminum, and beryllium form amphoteric oxides or hydroxides. Amphoterism depends on the oxidation state of the oxide.


For example, zinc oxide (ZnO) reacts with both acids and with bases: 


  • In ACID: ZnO + 2H+ -> Zn2+ + H2O

  • In BASE: ZnO + 2OH- + H2O -> [Zn(OH)4]2-


This reactivity can be used to separate different cations, such as zinc (II), which dissolves in base, from manganese (II), which does not dissolve in base.

Question: Which are the pharmaceutical applications of partition coefficient?I.  Predicts where drug will concentrate in the body II.  Predicts adverse drug interactions in the body III. Predicts solubility of a drug in water and fatty tissues in thebodyIV. Predicts how well a chemical ingredient will mix with creams    in consumer products

Question: What are the risks of the long-term use of benzodiazepines? I.  Developing tolerance II.  Developing acute stress reactions III. Developing dependence IV. Developing serious sleep problems
CorrectExplanation:
Benzodiazepines are commonly used to treat/manage acute stress reactions & serious sleep problems. The common risks associated with long-term use of BZDs are, inevitably, developing tolerance & dependence.


Mechanism of Action:

BZDs 🡪 ↑ channel opening frequency

BRBs 🡪 ↑ channel open duration

Question: Which of the following is not a primary standard?
CorrectExplanation:
A 🡪 1º std. for aq. alkalimetry, non aq. acidimetry

B 🡪 1º std. for complexometry

D 🡪 1º std. for iodometry


Additional Information:

Important requirements for 1º standard:

  • High purity
  • Atmospheric stability
  • Absence of hydrate of water
  • Reasonable solubility
  • Reasonably large molar mass
  • Modest cost

Question: Which of the following are B-Carboline derivatives isolated from sponges (Subphylum Tunicata)?

C 🡪  Purified carbohydrate extracted from brown seaweed by treatment of dilute alkali (BEQ!)

Question: A rule that states that when a stress is applied to a system in equilibrium, the equilibrium shifts to relieve the stress:
CorrectExplanation:
A 🡪 Formulated by Norwegian scientists Cato M. Guldberg & Peter Wage over the period of 1864-1879; law stating that the rate of any chemical reaction is proportional to the product of the masses of the reacting substances, with each mass raised to a power equal to the coefficient that occurs in the chemical equation. 

B 🡪 Discovered by Antoine Lavoisier in 1789; law stating that mass is neither created nor destroyed in chemical reactions.

D 🡪 Sometimes called the Proust’s Law or Law of Constant Composition; law stating that a given chemical compound always contains the same elements in the exact same proportions by mass.

Question: A sample drug excreted via the saliva:
CorrectExplanation:
Other drugs excreted via saliva include caffeine, phenytoin, and theophylline. Transfer of drugs from plasma into saliva appears to be largely dictated by passive diffusion. Because of this, only drugs in plasma that are not bound to proteins will be able to diffuse in saliva.

Question: Despite being the fastest drug against all erythrocytic stages of malaria parasites, artemisinin has gradually lost its popularity in the field of medicine due to the following reasons including:I.  Very short elimination half-life II.  Low bioavailability III. Rapidly and extensively metabolized in the body. IV. Not well established for the treatment of highly drug resistantmalarial strains.
CorrectExplanation: Artemisinins are derived extracts of sweet wormwood (Artemisia annua) and are well established for the treatment of malaria, including highly drug-resistant strains. Their efficacy also extends to phylogenetically unrelated parasitic infections such as schistosomiasis. However, despite the effectiveness of artemisinins, its role in the clinical field has decreased gradually due to the following scientifically proven inferences: (1) very short elimination half-life, which precludes their use for malaria prophylaxis; (2) poor solubility and erratic absorption that translates to low bioavailability; and (3) rapid & extensive metabolism in the body through CYP2B6, CYP3A4, and CYP2A6.
